Investigate Logon Events with EvtxECmd
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure EvtxECmd on Linux
Parse Windows Event Log files using EvtxECmd
Analyze logon and logoff events for suspicious activity patterns
Identify potential security threats through event correlation
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Windows Event Logs
Familiarity with Linux command line
Knowledge of authentication concepts
Understanding of CSV file formats
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated Linux machine. The provided machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required tools during the lab.

Task 1: Install EvtxECmd and Prepare Sample Data
Subtask 1.1: Install Required Dependencies
Install .NET runtime and wget:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y wget curl apt-transport-https
Install Microsoft package repository:

wget https://packages.microsoft.com/config/ubuntu/20.04/packages-microsoft-prod.deb -O packages-microsoft-prod.deb
sudo dpkg -i packages-microsoft-prod.deb
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y dotnet-runtime-6.0
Subtask 1.2: Download and Install EvtxECmd
Download EvtxECmd from Eric Zimmerman's tools:

cd /opt
sudo mkdir evtxecmd
cd evtxecmd
sudo wget https://f001.backblazeb2.com/file/EricZimmermanTools/EvtxECmd.zip
sudo apt install -y unzip
sudo unzip EvtxECmd.zip
sudo chmod +x EvtxECmd
Subtask 1.3: Create Sample Windows Event Log Files
Create a working directory and generate sample EVTX files:

mkdir ~/lab19
cd ~/lab19
Create a sample Security.evtx file with logon events:

# Download sample EVTX files for testing
wget https://github.com/sbousseaden/EVTX-ATTACK-SAMPLES/raw/master/Lateral%20Movement/sysmon_mimikatz_sekurlsa_logonpasswords.evtx -O sample_security.evtx
If the download fails, create a minimal test structure:

mkdir sample_logs
echo "Sample EVTX file for testing" > sample_logs/Security.evtx
Task 2: Parse Windows Event Logs with EvtxECmd
Subtask 2.1: Basic EVTX Parsing
Parse the sample EVTX file to CSV format:

sudo /opt/evtxecmd/EvtxECmd -f sample_security.evtx --csv ~/lab19 --csvf logon_events.csv
Verify the output:

ls -la ~/lab19/*.csv
head -5 ~/lab19/logon_events.csv
Subtask 2.2: Filter Logon-Specific Events
Parse and filter for authentication events (Event IDs 4624, 4625, 4634):

sudo /opt/evtxecmd/EvtxECmd -f sample_security.evtx --csv ~/lab19 --csvf filtered_logon.csv --inc 4624,4625,4634
Subtask 2.3: Parse Multiple EVTX Files
If you have multiple EVTX files, parse an entire directory:

# Create additional sample files
cp sample_security.evtx sample_system.evtx
sudo /opt/evtxecmd/EvtxECmd -d . --csv ~/lab19 --csvf all_events.csv
Task 3: Analyze Logon and Logoff Events for Suspicious Activity
Subtask 3.1: Examine Logon Event Structure
View the CSV structure and key fields:

head -1 ~/lab19/logon_events.csv | tr ',' '\n' | nl
Extract key logon information:

# View specific columns for logon analysis
cut -d',' -f1,2,3,7,8 ~/lab19/logon_events.csv | head -10
Subtask 3.2: Identify Failed Logon Attempts
Create a script to analyze failed logons:

cat > analyze_logons.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Logon Event Analysis ==="
echo

# Check if CSV file exists
if [ ! -f "logon_events.csv" ]; then
    echo "No logon events CSV found. Creating sample data..."
    cat > logon_events.csv << 'CSVEOF'
TimeCreated,EventId,Level,Keywords,Channel,Computer,UserId,UserName,LogonType,Status
2024-01-15 09:15:23,4624,Information,Audit Success,Security,WORKSTATION01,S-1-5-21-123456789,john.doe,2,0x0
2024-01-15 09:16:45,4625,Information,Audit Failure,Security,WORKSTATION01,S-1-5-21-123456789,admin,2,0xC000006D
2024-01-15 09:17:12,4625,Information,Audit Failure,Security,WORKSTATION01,S-1-5-21-123456789,admin,2,0xC000006D
2024-01-15 09:18:33,4624,Information,Audit Success,Security,WORKSTATION01,S-1-5-21-123456789,jane.smith,10,0x0
